	   <tr><td colspan=2>One thing that you cannot forget is that your pet also represents yet another get-out-of-death free card. Sometimes you will medding, moving to a different pull spot, etc. and you will get jumped by a creature that cons red that will beat the holy hell out of you. Assuming you havent lost so many hps in the initial attack that your agility has dropped, you can turn and run. Your pet will attack and taunt the creature automatically, and if you haven't attacked the monster then it will turn on your pet. The monster will then demolish your pet, but those few rounds can be enough time for you to get away, assuming you have somewhere to run to and proceed there in a straight line. Granted, this strategy becomes less important once you get feign death, but my pets noble sacrifice saved my life many times in my youth. When you consider the cost of a pet is just 2 chips and a bubble of mana (depending on race, etc.), the only time I wouldnt use a pet is when Im pulling for a group (it gets in the way sometimes) or in some dungeons where it will get confused and possibly start a train.&nbsp;&nbsp;And trust me, SK's are not the greatest at 'taking a lot of hits', and siphon strength has virtually no effect on the attack power of enemies as time goes on. Pets are well worth the cost, in this long-winded knight's opinion.<br>&nbsp;<br>Nazragul Xarn, 40th Season Knight of the Dismal Rage<br>Morell-Thule</td></tr>
